235","1312":"1312","1287":"1287","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","before 1284":"before 1284","1329":"1329","New Castile, España":"New Castile, Spain","Toledo, Toledo, Castile-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","España":"Spain","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Spain","Villabáñez, Valladolid, Castilla y León, España":"Villabáñez, Valladolid, Castilla y León, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osorio","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Francisco, Jorge, Miguel, Mario, Jaime, Manuel, Rafael, Ana.  Portuguese Agostinho, Marcio.","Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Osório</b>): from a medieval personal name <i>Osorius</i>, of uncertain origin. It is perhaps a metathesized form of Latin <i>Orosius</i> (Greek <i>Orosios</i>, a derivative of <i>oros</i> ‘mountain’), the name borne by a 4th-century Iberian theologian and historian, who was famous in Spain throughout the Middle Ages. Compare   Ozorio  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Osornio","meanings":["Hispanic (Mexico): probably an altered form of Spanish   Osorio  , influenced by   Osorno  ."]},{"name":"Osoria","meanings":["Spanish: from the personal name <i>Osoria</i>, feminine form of   Osorio  . This surname is most common in the Dominican Republic, Mexico, and Cuba. Compare   Ozoria  ."]},{"name":"Ozorio","meanings":["Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Ozório</b>): variant of   Osorio  ."]}]},{"name":"Elvira","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Germanic (Visigothic) origin , very common in the Middle Ages. It was not used in the English-speaking world until the 19th century, when it was made familiar as the name of the long-suffering wife of  Don Juan , both in  Mozart's  opera Don Giovanni (  1789 ) and in  Byron's  satirical epic poem Don Juan (  1819–24 ). In his comedy Blithe Spirit  Noel Coward  used it as the name of  Charles Condomine's  first wife, who returns to haunt him. It is also the name of the heroine of the Swedish film Elvira Madigan (  1967 ), directed by  Bo Widerberg , a romantic tragedy about a pair of lovers who would rather die than be separated."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Álvarez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Luis, Carlos, Jesus, Francisco, Jorge, Ramon, Pedro, Miguel, Roberto.  Portuguese Catarina, Lidio, Ligia, Joaquim, Wenceslao.","Spanish (<b>Álvarez</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Álvaro</i> (see   Alvaro  ). Compare   Alavarez  ,   Albares  ,   Albarez  ,   Alvares  , and   Alverez  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Alverez","meanings":["(1997: 275;2007: 1656; 2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Alberto, Alfredo, Francisco, Mario, Miguel, Ramon, Carlos, Javier, Luis, Manuel, Marcelino.","Hispanic (<b>Álverez</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Álvarez</b> (see   Alvarez  )."]},{"name":"Albares","meanings":["Spanish: variant of <b>Álvarez</b> (see   Alvarez  )."]},{"name":"Alavarez","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Álvarez</b> (see   Alvarez  )."]},{"name":"Alvaro","meanings":["Visigothic: of uncertain etymology."]},{"name":"Albarez","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Álbarez</b>): variant of <b>Álvarez</b> (see   Alvarez  ). This surname is very rare in Spain."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elvira Álvarez Osorio was born in 1258, in New Castile, Spain, her father, Álvar Rodríguez Osorio de Villalobos I Señor de Villaornate, was 28 and her mother, Elvira Nuñez de Astorga, was 23. She married García Gómez Carrillo de Molina before 1284, in New Castile, Spai